        "id": 3067252,
        "name": "Maxwell A.",
        "username": "Maxwell_A",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/m/67e7ee/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2021-01-10T04:39:05.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>I\u2019ve only had good experiences with Marguet Champagnes. Has anyone had issues with bottle variation or flawed bottles? Even though he adds little to no SO2, the wines seem to have a pretty good track record.</p>\n<p>I remember seeing this a while back and stumbled across it again - John Gilman\u2019s two reviews of Benoit Marguet\u2019s Crayeres 2014. He is typically very pleased with the bottling but says he experienced \u201cnatural wine mousiness\u201d in two different bottles.</p>\n<p>\u201cThe 2014 Les Cray\u00e8res from Beno\u00eet Marguet is a deep, complex and beautifully soil-driven example of the vintage, but there is just a touch of natural wine \u201cmousiness\u201d here that I hope will age out of the wine with some bottle age, as everything else about this wine is truly stunning.\u201d (an excerpt from his review)</p>\n<p>Any other tasting notes I can find are positive and have no mention of this. I\u2019d be interested to hear from anyone that has tried this specific bottling or has had similar experiences with Marguet Champagnes.</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 8,
        "updated_at": "2022-06-04T01:00:56.560Z",
